l\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2O3/c1-2(8)3-4(9)7-5(10)6-3/h2-3,8H,1H3,(H2,6,7,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated hydrogenation of CO2 on iron-sulfur mineral sites yields reduced one-carbon species, with formate as the first stable product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the hydrothermal CO2 reduction chemistry assigned to greigite/mackinawite under alkaline vent conditions and reflects FeS/Fe3S4-mediated C1 fixation emphasized for early metabolism; vent mineral formation and relevance are supported by White et al. (2015) and vent thermodynamic favorability by Shock and Canovas (1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation to acetate and pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and elemental iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor/alkaline hydrothermal setting, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction and carbon-carbon bond formation on iron oxide/metal surfaces produce acetate and higher alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate from reduced carbon intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate formation from iron-sulfur/carbonyl chemistry under hydrothermal conditions is consistent with Cody et al. (2000), while hydrothermal amino-acid-favorable carbon fixation is thermodynamically supported by Shock and Canovas (1998). This step is a network-connecting abstraction grounded in documented hydrothermal pyruvate accessibility.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and vent-derived aldehyde formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mixing-zone compatible hydrothermal conversion, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced carbon pools undergo mineral-catalyzed conversion to small aldehydes through Fischer-Tropsch-type and carbonyl chemistry, supplying acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to surface environments.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite-catalyzed hydrothermal production of aldehydes is aligned with Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis in vent systems and provides plausible linkage from vent carbon fixation to aldehyde feedstocks. The role of hydrothermal mineral catalysis and metabolically relevant carbonyl products is supported by Cody et al. (2000), Shock and Canovas (1998), and White et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark discharge generation of HCN and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces collecting discharge products\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"electric discharge in CH4/N2/H2O or CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S atmospheres followed by aqueous trapping in mineral-rich pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Atmospheric energy input generates nitriles and aldehydes, which are scavenged into surface waters where mineral surfaces concentrate them.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Threonine and allothreonine were detected in classic spark discharge experiments where HCN, NH3, and aldehydes are generated in situ; this step captures the literature-supported origin of key feedstocks from discharge chemistry. Supported by Ring et al. (1972), Johnson et al. (2008), and Parker et al. (2011). The mineral agents represent surface collection/concentration rather than the energetic discharge source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system with sulfide mineral context and UV-active TiO2 surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, H2S present, phosphate-buffered surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox cycling of cyanide with sulfide reductant performs reductive homologation of HCN through Kiliani-Fischer-like chemistry to furnish glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015) experimentally established UV/H2S/Cu cyanide photoredox homologation of HCN to sugars including glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde in surface cyanosulfidic chemistry. The surface mineral agents encode the required sulfide-rich, UV-exposed mineral setting.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoredox conversion of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system in sulfide-rich UV-irradiated pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation for about 2 h, H2S reductant, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN; subsequent photoreduction under cyanosulfidic conditions converts the cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is directly based on the experimentally demonstrated sequence of Ritson and Sutherland (2013), who reported photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde at 19% yield under UV/H2S/Cu(I)-cyanide conditions. Patel et al. (2015) embeds this in a broader cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV hydration of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis with phosphate-rich pool chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pools, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydration and rearrangement of cyanide-derived species yields formamide as a concentrated nitrogen-carbon intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a recognized UV-accessible HCN derivative in prebiotic surface chemistry and helps connect HCN-rich chemistry to broader aminonitrile/nucleobase networks. Its inclusion is consistent with the UV/HCN surface framework discussed in Patel et al. (2015) and broader formamide photochemistry invoked in prebiotic synthesis studies; this connection is somewhat network-completion oriented but remains plausible and literature-compatible.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine from HCN and formal C1 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite concentration with UV-exposed surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker-type pool chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrogen-carbon feedstocks form an imine-equivalent and cyanated intermediate, followed by hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycine is one of the dominant products in discharge and HCN-based prebiotic systems and serves as the glycine branch required for the proposed reverse aldol route to threonine. Supported generally by Ring et al. (1972), Parker et al. (2011), and Patel et al. (2015). This specific condensed representation is a network simplification to preserve connectivity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent formation of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde or glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate stabilization of aldehydes with montmorillonite concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strecker conditions; either lactaldehyde or glyceraldehyde can serve as aldehyde entry point; racemic and diastereomeric products expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine, HCN adds to generate the aminonitrile, and the product pool contains the threonine aminonitrile precursor ensemble.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Lactaldehyde is the experimentally defined direct Strecker precursor to threonine aminonitrile, and Patel et al. (2015) further identifies a parallel route via glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN. Ritson and Sutherland (2013) demonstrated the lactaldehyde sequence; Patel et al. (2015) placed both entries in the cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration in evaporitic pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonium carbonate/CO2-rich setting, hydantoin-forming conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide and ammonium carbonate equivalents to form a cyclic hydantoin thermodynamic sink.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) experimentally demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs conversion of alpha-keto-acid-derived systems to amino acids via hydantoins and emphasized hydantoins as thermodynamic sinks; extending this to lactaldehyde gives 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin as the literature-supported threonine analogue proposed in the review. Hydantoins in meteorites support plausibility (Lerner and Cooper, 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol-like assembly of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate from pyruvate-derived keto chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ in solution or Ni catalytic surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic prebiotic pool; keto-acid network step required to connect hydrothermal pyruvate to threonine keto precursor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Prebiotic keto-acid network chemistry extends and hydroxylates pyruvate-derived carbon skeletons to give the alpha-keto-beta-hydroxy precursor of threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The specific prebiotic synthesis of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate is not directly demonstrated in the cited literature, so this step is explicitly network-completing and somewhat speculative. Its inclusion is justified because Muchowska et al. (2019) established Fe2+-promoted reductive amination of alpha-keto acids, Kaur et al. (2024) showed H2-driven reductive amination over nickel at 22C and pH 8, and Huber and Wachtershauser (2006) showed homologous alpha-hydroxy/alpha-amino acid generation on Ni-Fe precipitates, supporting accessibility of the threonine keto precursor within prebiotic keto-acid chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and reductive amination routes to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"water-driven hydrolysis, Fe2+ or Ni for reductive amination where applicable\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"low-temperature pools favored because threonine is unstable at elevated temperature; pH ~8 for Ni/H2 reductive amination branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three literature-supported endgame modes converge: hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile, hydrolysis of the hydantoin intermediate, and reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine follows the Strecker route of Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015); hydantoin hydrolysis follows the Bucherer-Bergs logic of Pulletikurti et al. (2022); reductive amination of the threonine keto precursor is inferred from alpha-keto-acid amination chemistry demonstrated by Muchowska et al. (2019) and Kaur et al. (2024). The low-temperature emphasis is required by threonine instability discussed by Truong et al. (2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Canonical Ritson-Sutherland path from HCN-derived acetaldehyde to lactaldehyde, then Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Patel-Sutherland parallel route in which cyanosulfidic homologation supplies glyceraldehyde, which directly enters Strecker chemistry to the threonine aminonitrile and then threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface aldehyde relay route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent carbon fixation produces acetate/pyruvate and then aldehydes; acetaldehyde is exported to UV-exposed pools, reduced to lactaldehyde, and converted through Strecker chemistry to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal aldehydes feed surface sugar chemistry, converging on glyceraldehyde and then threonine aminonitrile formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric discharge directly supplies HCN and acetaldehyde, bypassing hydrothermal carbon fixation before entering the lactaldehyde Strecker sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide, ammonia, and carbon dioxide to form a hydantoin sink that hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldehyde to hydantoin route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived acetaldehyde is converted in surface pools to lactaldehyde, then captured as hydantoin and hydrolyzed to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-keto acid reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate enters a prebiotic keto-acid network to form 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate, which is reductively aminated to threonine under mild biochemical conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine-acetaldehyde aldol-derived route\",\n      \"description\": \"Discharge/cyanide chemistry supplies glycine and acetaldehyde; these converge conceptually on the threonine carbon skeleton and are represented through the connected aminonitrile node and final hydrolysis route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Integrated cyanosulfidic-protometabolic network route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN homologation yields glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde while vent chemistry yields pyruvate and acetaldehyde; both modules converge through aminonitrile and keto-acid branches to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets threonine by integrating literature-supported prebiotic routes centered on shared carbon-nitrogen hubs. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1/C2/C3 feedstocks such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and glycolaldehyde via iron-sulfur and magnetite catalysis under vent conditions. Surface cyanosulfidic photochemistry then converts HCN-derived aldehyde pools into threonine precursors through experimentally supported lactaldehyde and glyceraldehyde entries, while HCN oligomerization, discharge-derived HCN, and aldehyde-ammonia chemistry provide convergent access to aminonitriles and related intermediates. Biochemical/prebiotic stages convert the aminonitrile, hydantoin, and alpha-keto precursor pools into threonine under lower-temperature conditions more compatible with threonine stability. The ten pathways are not ten wholly unique reaction sets; rather, they are ten valid routes through a single connected bipartite network, reflecting the literature's emphasis on network convergence around HCN, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile, and 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetate/acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H7NO", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)2-4(5)6/h3,7H,2H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(4(7)8)6/h2,6H,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2O3/c1-2(8)3-4(9)7-5(10)6-3/h2-3,8H,1H3,(H2,6,7,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated hydrogenation of CO2 on iron-sulfur mineral sites yields reduced one-carbon species, with formate as the first stable product.", "reasoning": "This follows the hydrothermal CO2 reduction chemistry assigned to greigite/mackinawite under alkaline vent conditions and reflects FeS/Fe3S4-mediated C1 fixation emphasized for early metabolism; vent mineral formation and relevance are supported by White et al. (2015) and vent thermodynamic favorability by Shock and Canovas (1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation to acetate and pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and elemental iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor/alkaline hydrothermal setting, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and carbon-carbon bond formation on iron oxide/metal surfaces produce acetate and higher alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate from reduced carbon intermediates.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate formation from iron-sulfur/carbonyl chemistry under hydrothermal conditions is consistent with Cody et al. (2000), while hydrothermal amino-acid-favorable carbon fixation is thermodynamically supported by Shock and Canovas (1998). This step is a network-connecting abstraction grounded in documented hydrothermal pyruvate accessibility."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type and vent-derived aldehyde formation", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mixing-zone compatible hydrothermal conversion, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Reduced carbon pools undergo mineral-catalyzed conversion to small aldehydes through Fischer-Tropsch-type and carbonyl chemistry, supplying acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to surface environments.", "reasoning": "Magnetite-catalyzed hydrothermal production of aldehydes is aligned with Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis in vent systems and provides plausible linkage from vent carbon fixation to aldehyde feedstocks. The role of hydrothermal mineral catalysis and metabolically relevant carbonyl products is supported by Cody et al. (2000), Shock and Canovas (1998), and White et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Spark discharge generation of HCN and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces collecting discharge products", "aqueous": "true", "other": "electric discharge in CH4/N2/H2O or CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S atmospheres followed by aqueous trapping in mineral-rich pools"}, "mechanism": "Atmospheric energy input generates nitriles and aldehydes, which are scavenged into surface waters where mineral surfaces concentrate them.", "reasoning": "Threonine and allothreonine were detected in classic spark discharge experiments where HCN, NH3, and aldehydes are generated in situ; this step captures the literature-supported origin of key feedstocks from discharge chemistry. Supported by Ring et al. (1972), Johnson et al. (2008), and Parker et al. (2011). The mineral agents represent surface collection/concentration rather than the energetic discharge source."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system with sulfide mineral context and UV-active TiO2 surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, H2S present, phosphate-buffered surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox cycling of cyanide with sulfide reductant performs reductive homologation of HCN through Kiliani-Fischer-like chemistry to furnish glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015) experimentally established UV/H2S/Cu cyanide photoredox homologation of HCN to sugars including glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde in surface cyanosulfidic chemistry. The surface mineral agents encode the required sulfide-rich, UV-exposed mineral setting."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Photoredox conversion of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system in sulfide-rich UV-irradiated pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation for about 2 h, H2S reductant, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN; subsequent photoreduction under cyanosulfidic conditions converts the cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is directly based on the experimentally demonstrated sequence of Ritson and Sutherland (2013), who reported photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde at 19% yield under UV/H2S/Cu(I)-cyanide conditions. Patel et al. (2015) embeds this in a broader cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV hydration of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis with phosphate-rich pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pools, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration and rearrangement of cyanide-derived species yields formamide as a concentrated nitrogen-carbon intermediate.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a recognized UV-accessible HCN derivative in prebiotic surface chemistry and helps connect HCN-rich chemistry to broader aminonitrile/nucleobase networks. Its inclusion is consistent with the UV/HCN surface framework discussed in Patel et al. (2015) and broader formamide photochemistry invoked in prebiotic synthesis studies; this connection is somewhat network-completion oriented but remains plausible and literature-compatible."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine from HCN and formal C1 feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentration with UV-exposed surface setting", "aqueous": "true", "ot