 "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration in evaporitic pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonium carbonate/CO2-rich setting, hydantoin-forming conditions"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide and ammonium carbonate equivalents to form a cyclic hydantoin thermodynamic sink.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (2022) experimentally demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs conversion of alpha-keto-acid-derived systems to amino acids via hydantoins and emphasized hydantoins as thermodynamic sinks; extending this to lactaldehyde gives 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin as the literature-supported threonine analogue proposed in the review. Hydantoins in meteorites support plausibility (Lerner and Cooper, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Aldol-like assembly of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate from pyruvate-derived keto chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+ in solution or Ni catalytic surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic prebiotic pool; keto-acid network step required to connect hydrothermal pyruvate to threonine keto precursor"}, "mechanism": "Prebiotic keto-acid network chemistry extends and hydroxylates pyruvate-derived carbon skeletons to give the alpha-keto-beta-hydroxy precursor of threonine.", "reasoning": "The specific prebiotic synthesis of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate is not directly demonstrated in the cited literature, so this step is explicitly network-completing and somewhat speculative. Its inclusion is justified because Muchowska et al. (2019) established Fe2+-promoted reductive amination of alpha-keto acids, Kaur et al. (2024) showed H2-driven reductive amination over nickel at 22C and pH 8, and Huber and Wachtershauser (2006) showed homologous alpha-hydroxy/alpha-amino acid generation on Ni-Fe precipitates, supporting accessibility of the threonine keto precursor within prebiotic keto-acid chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis and reductive amination routes to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_016", "mol_015", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "water-driven hydrolysis, Fe2+ or Ni for reductive amination where applicable", "aqueous": "true", "other": "low-temperature pools favored because threonine is unstable at elevated temperature; pH ~8 for Ni/H2 reductive amination branch"}, "mechanism": "Three literature-supported endgame modes converge: hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile, hydrolysis of the hydantoin intermediate, and reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine follows the Strecker route of Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015); hydantoin hydrolysis follows the Bucherer-Bergs logic of Pulletikurti et al. (2022); reductive amination of the threonine keto precursor is inferred from alpha-keto-acid amination chemistry demonstrated by Muchowska et al. (2019) and Kaur et al. (2024). The low-temperature emphasis is required by threonine instability discussed by Truong et al. (2019)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Canonical Ritson-Sutherland path from HCN-derived acetaldehyde to lactaldehyde, then Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Glyceraldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Patel-Sutherland parallel route in which cyanosulfidic homologation supplies glyceraldehyde, which directly enters Strecker chemistry to the threonine aminonitrile and then threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface aldehyde relay route", "description": "Vent carbon fixation produces acetate/pyruvate and then aldehydes; acetaldehyde is exported to UV-exposed pools, reduced to lactaldehyde, and converted through Strecker chemistry to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde route", "description": "Hydrothermal aldehydes feed surface sugar chemistry, converging on glyceraldehyde and then threonine aminonitrile formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Spark-discharge Strecker route", "description": "Atmospheric discharge directly supplies HCN and acetaldehyde, bypassing hydrothermal carbon fixation before entering the lactaldehyde Strecker sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route from lactaldehyde", "description": "Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide, ammonia, and carbon dioxide to form a hydantoin sink that hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal aldehyde to hydantoin route", "description": "Vent-derived acetaldehyde is converted in surface pools to lactaldehyde, then captured as hydantoin and hydrolyzed to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Alpha-keto acid reduct