{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T02:53:46.741381", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of threonine: routes, evidence, and unsolved puzzles\n\n**Threonine emerges as one of the most prebiotically accessible yet paradoxically fragile proteinogenic amino acids.** The cyanosulfidic chemistry developed by Sutherland and colleagues demonstrates that threonine's Strecker precursor forms as an \"inevitable by-product\" of the same HCN photoredox chemistry that generates ribonucleotide building blocks \u2014 linking amino acid and RNA origins in a single reaction network (Patel et al., *Nature Chemistry*, 2015). Yet threonine's \u03b2-hydroxyl group renders it among the least stable amino acids under prebiotic conditions, unable to persist beyond **1 billion years even at 0\u00b0C** in aqueous solution (Truong et al., *Icarus*, 2019). This tension between facile synthesis and rapid degradation defines threonine's unique position in origin-of-life chemistry and frames the central challenge: not how to make it, but how to use it before it decomposes.\n\n---\n\n## Five demonstrated routes from simple molecules to threonine\n\nMultiple independent pathways connect simple prebiotic feedstocks (HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082O, H\u2082S, CH\u2084, UV light) to threonine. Each proceeds through distinct intermediates and operates under different environmental conditions, suggesting that threonine could have formed in diverse early Earth settings.\n\n### Route 1: Strecker synthesis via lactaldehyde (cyanosulfidic pathway)\n\nThe most completely characterized route proceeds through **lactaldehyde** (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key aldehyde precursor. Ritson and Sutherland (*Angewandte Chemie International Edition*, 2013) demonstrated each step experimentally: UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H\u2082S as reductant converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. Acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, which undergoes photoreduction to lactaldehyde at **19% yield** after 2 hours of irradiation. Lactaldehyde then undergoes classic Strecker chemistry \u2014 reaction with NH\u2083 to form an imine, followed by HCN addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (the threonine aminonitrile), which hydrolyzes to threonine and allothreonine as a racemic mixture of diastereomers. The complete pathway requires only HCN, H\u2082O, H\u2082S, Cu minerals, and UV light \u2014 all prebiotically plausible.\n\nPatel et al. (*Nature Chemistry*, 2015) placed this route within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism, showing that the threonine aminonitrile is one of four amino acid precursors (alongside those for glycine, alanine, and serine) that arise as \"inevitable by-products\" of the Kiliani\u2013Fischer reductive homologation of HCN that also produces ribonucleotide precursors. A parallel route through glyceraldehyde (rather than lactaldehyde) provides a second entry point: glyceraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile.\n\n### Route 2: Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis\n\nElectric discharge experiments have confirmed threonine production from simple gas mixtures. **Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller** (*Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 1972) provided the first confirmed detection, using spark discharge on CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O with traces of NH\u2083. Both threonine and allothreonine were identified by ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS, alongside over 20 other amino acids. The mechanism proceeds through in situ generation of HCN, NH\u2083, and aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) followed by aqueous Strecker synthesis.\n\nReanalysis of Stanley Miller's archived experimental samples revealed additional threonine detections. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, and Bada (*PNAS*, 2011) analyzed Miller's unreported 1958 H\u2082S-containing experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/CO\u2082/H\u2082S gas mixture) and detected **23 amino acids including threonine** \u2014 which appeared in the H\u2082S experiment but not in the three other discharge configurations (original, volcanic, silent). The presence of H\u2082S apparently promoted formation of hydroxylated and sulfur-containing amino acids. Johnson et al. (*Science*, 2008) found that Miller's volcanic apparatus (incorporating hot water mist) preferentially synthesized hydroxylated compounds, with **22 amino acids** total. All products were racemic, confirming abiotic origin.\n\n### Route 3: Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde\n\nThe biological retro-aldol cleavage of threonine (catalyzed by threonine aldolases) yields glycine + acetaldehyde. The reverse \u2014 aldol condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde \u2014 represents a conceptually simple prebiotic route, since both glycine and acetaldehyde rank among the most abundant prebiotic molecules. However, this condensation is **thermodynamically unfavorable** and requires either high glycine concentrations or catalytic assistance to proceed (Fesko, *Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology*, 2016). Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomers form. No purely prebiotic demonstration of this specific aldol condensation has been reported, though the reaction defines the structural relationship between threonine and its simplest precursors.\n\nKoga and Naraoka (*ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*, 2022) demonstrated a related pathway: \u00b9\u00b3C-labeled aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) reacting with ammonia in aqueous solution produced families of **hydroxy amino acids including C\u2083 and C\u2084 structural isomers** that match the distribution found in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites. This ammonia-aldehyde chemistry provides a route to threonine-related compounds without requiring HCN.\n\n### Route 4: Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids\n\nThe keto acid precursor to threonine is **2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate** (\u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate). Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (*Nature*, 2019) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70\u00b0C, producing glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate from their corresponding keto acids. Kaur et al. (*Chem*, 2024) extended this to H\u2082-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at **22\u00b0C and pH 8**. While threonine's specific keto acid precursor was not tested in either study, the principle is established. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 2006) demonstrated CO-dependent formation of \u03b1-hydroxy and \u03b1-amino acids (including the serine analog, bearing a HOCH\u2082 substituent) at 80\u2013120\u00b0C on Ni-Fe precipitates, suggesting that the threonine homolog (bearing a CH\u2083CHOH substituent) could form via the same chain-elongation mechanism.\n\n### Route 5: Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway\n\nThe Bucherer-Bergs reaction (aldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 amino acid) provides a thermodynamic advantage over direct Strecker synthesis because the hydantoin intermediate acts as a thermodynamic sink. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (*Nature Chemistry*, 2022) demonstrated this pathway for several \u03b1-keto acids \u2192 amino acids, showing that pyruvate converts to alanine via 5-methylhydantoin and that the chemistry parallels extant biosynthetic pathways. For threonine, lactaldehyde would react with HCN and ammonium carbonate to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin, which hydrolyzes to threonine. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner and Cooper, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 2005), consistent with this pathway operating in meteorite parent bodies.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and their roles as branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of threonine intersects with several other biosynthetic pathways through shared intermediates, creating a network rather than a linear sequence.\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (2-hydroxypropanal) is the most direct aldehyde precursor specific to threonine via Strecker chemistry. It forms through UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin at 19% yield (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013). **Glycolaldehyde** serves as the crucial branch point between sugar chemistry and amino acid chemistry \u2014 it enters the formose reaction to produce ribose precursors and simultaneously provides the carbon skeleton for serine (via Strecker) and connects to threonine through further homologation. Its detection in the interstellar medium toward IRAS 16293-2422 and in precometary ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., *PNAS*, 2015) confirms its cosmochemical availability. **Glyceraldehyde** occupies the next node: it is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and directly reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 to form the threonine aminonitrile, making it perhaps the single most important branch point connecting RNA and protein precursor chemistry.\n\n**Acetaldehyde** connects to threonine through two routes \u2014 Strecker synthesis (producing alanine directly, or lactaldehyde via cyanohydrin reduction, then threonine) and aldol condensation with glycine. It is among the simplest and most abundant products of spark discharge experiments and interstellar chemistry. **\u03b1-Ketobutyrate** represents the metabolic connection: in modern biochemistry, threonine dehydratase converts threonine to \u03b1-ketobutyrate, and the reverse (reductive amination) constitutes a plausible prebiotic route. Copley, Smith, and Morowitz (*PNAS*, 2005) proposed that \u03b1-keto acids formed esters with dinucleotides in a proto-metabolic amino acid synthesis, providing selectivity through nucleotide-keto acid interactions. **HCN oligomers** represent a less specific but broad-spectrum source: Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (*Life*, 2013) reviewed 24 experimental conditions and found that **12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids**, including threonine, were detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates, with glycine and aspartic acid consistently the most abundant products.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental settings and their suitability for each synthetic step\n\nDifferent prebiotic environments favor different steps in threonine synthesis, and no single setting optimizes the entire pathway. This \"conditions compatibility problem\" is a central challenge.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City type, 40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311) provide the most favorable thermodynamic conditions for amino acid synthesis. Shock and Canovas (*Science*, 1998) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of all 20 amino acids is exergonic in hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions. White, Bhartia, and Russell (*Earth and Planetary Science Letters*, 2015) demonstrated that mackinawite (FeS) and greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) precipitate in simulated Hadean chimney walls at 40\u201380\u00b0C, with maximum greigite yield at 75\u00b0C. Greigite's Fe\u2084S\u2084 cubane units are structural analogs of active centers in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin. Lane and Martin (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*, 2012) showed that Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores could concentrate organics approximately **5,000-fold** via thermophoresis, partially addressing the concentration problem.\n\n**Surface volcanic hot springs and evaporitic pools** favor condensation reactions and UV-driven photochemistry. Damer and Deamer (*Astrobiology*, 2020) proposed that volcanic hot spring pools with wet-dry cycling at 60\u201380\u00b0C drive peptide and RNA-like polymer formation. The cyanosulfidic chemistry of Sutherland operates optimally in surface UV-exposed pools with phosphate buffer at ~35\u00b0C. Lahav, White, and Chang (*Science*, 1978) showed that wet-dry cycling plus temperature cycling in clay environments produces longer oligopeptides in higher yields than temperature fluctuations alone. Campbell et al. (*Nature Communications*, 2019) demonstrated that deliquescent minerals can mediate autonomous wet-dry cycling via humidity changes, achieving **over 10-fold higher oligomerization yields**.\n\n**Black smoker hydrothermal vents** (250\u2013400\u00b0C) are problematic. Bada, Miller, and Zhao (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995) demonstrated that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C**. However, the mixing zones where hot fluid encounters cold seawater (100\u2013150\u00b0C) remain viable. Marshall (*Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 1994) synthesized amino acids at 200\u2013275\u00b0C from aqueous NH\u2084HCO\u2083 with hydrocarbons, though no synthesis occurred below 150\u00b0C. The synthesis-destruction balance is precarious: Aubrey et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2009) concluded that equilibrium at high temperatures favors net degradation rather than synthesis.\n\n**Ice environments** offer a counterintuitive advantage. Eutectic freezing concentrates solutes in brine channels between ice crystals. Miyakawa et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2002) froze NH\u2084CN solutions for 25 years at -20\u00b0C and -78\u00b0C, producing adenine, guanine, and amino acids \u2014 demonstrating that cold environments can drive prebiotic chemistry while simultaneously protecting labile products from thermal degradation.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts accelerate and direct threonine-relevant reactions\n\nMineral surfaces play three critical roles in prebiotic amino acid chemistry: catalyzing bond formation, concentrating dilute reactants, and potentially inducing chiral selectivity.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** anchor W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 1998) demonstrated peptide formation from amino acids activated by CO on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces at 100\u00b0C, achieving dipeptide yields of **0.4\u201312.4%** and tripeptide yields of ~0.10%. Their 2006 work (*Science*) showed CO-dependent \u03b1-amino acid synthesis on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80\u2013120\u00b0C using cyano ligands as the C/N source. Pyrite (FeS\u2082) shows particularly interesting photocatalytic properties: a 2024 study in *Nature Communications* demonstrated that natural pyrite produces D-amino acids with enantiomeric excess of **14.5\u201342.4%** via asymmetric photocatalytic reductive amination \u2014 the first demonstration of a mineral surface generating significant chiral bias in amino acid synthesis. Cody, Boctor, and Hazen (*Science*, 2000) showed that carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds produce pyruvate from CO and FeS at hydrothermal conditions, establishing the availability of key \u03b1-keto acid precursors.\n\n**Clay minerals**, particularly montmorillonite, catalyze condensation and polymerization. Ferris et al. (*Nature*, 1996) achieved RNA oligomers up to 50 nucleotides on montmorillonite surfaces. For amino acids, Kitadai et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2015) showed that glycine on montmorillonite at 150\u00b0C for 336 hours converts **~13.9% of monomers** to peptides under dry conditions, with no peptides forming without the mineral. Montmorillonite's interlayer structure provides steric effects that enhance condensation while protecting macromolecules from thermal decomposition. Bujd\u00e1k et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995) demonstrated hetero-oligomerization (ala-gly-gly from ala + gly\u2082) on Ca-montmorillonite during wet-dry cycling at 80\u00b0C, with approximately 10% oligomer yields after 3 weeks.\n\n**Photocatalytic minerals** offer UV-driven synthesis pathways. ZnS surfaces drive reversible reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids (Wang et al., *Chemical Communications*, 2012), supporting Mulkidjanian's zinc world hypothesis (*Biology Direct*, 2009) that life emerged at photosynthetically active porous ZnS structures. TiO\u2082 has been shown to catalyze amino acid production from simple precursors under near-UV illumination (Dunn, Aikawa, and Bard, *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, 1981). Both minerals could have driven amino acid synthesis in shallow, UV-exposed prebiotic pools.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and experimental evidence establishes threonine's abiotic credentials\n\nThe detection of threonine in extraterrestrial materials provides independent confirmation that abiotic synthesis occurs under natural conditions, though contamination complicates interpretation.\n\nThe strongest evidence for indigenous extraterrestrial threonine comes from the **CR2 chondrite GRA 95229** (Graves Nunataks, Antarctica). Pizzarello et al. (*PNAS*, 2012) positively identified threonine and allothreonine alongside other hydroxy amino acids, with the critical observation that **threonine was racemic** \u2014 consistent with abiotic synthesis and ruling out biological contamination. The pristine Antarctic collection conditions and the absence of L-excess make this the most compelling meteoritic detection. In the Murchison meteorite, threonine has been detected at approximately **700 ppb** for L-threonine, but the strong L-enrichment (~99% Lee) is attributed to terrestrial contamination (Kato et al., *Scientific Reports*, 2017; Glavin et al., *Meteoritics and Planetary Science*, 2020). Similarly, Tagish Lake analyses showed ~99% Lee for threonine (Glavin et al., 2012), again flagged as contamination. Only **12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids** have been confirmed in meteorites with indigenous signatures.\n\nInterstellar ice analog experiments provide complementary evidence. Nuevo et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2008) tentatively detected threonine in organic residues from vacuum UV irradiation of ice mixtures (H\u2082O, CO, CO\u2082, CH\u2083OH, CH\u2084, NH\u2083) at 10\u201380 K \u2014 the first such detection in ice photolysis experiments. Separately, UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H\u2082O + NH\u2083 ice at 15 K produced 13 amino acids including threonine (Nuevo et al., *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*, 2008). These experiments demonstrate that threonine can form through non-aqueous photochemistry in interstellar environments.\n\nQuantitative yields from laboratory experiments remain low. In spark discharge experiments, threonine appears at trace levels relative to glycine (the dominant product). Weber (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1998) achieved 0.08% homoserine (threonine's biosynthetic precursor) from formaldehyde + glycolaldehyde + NH\u2084Cl with thiol catalyst at 40\u00b0C over 35 days. The cyanosulfidic pathway achieves 19% yield for the lactaldehyde intermediate, but overall threonine yields through the complete Strecker sequence remain unquantified in the published literature.\n\n---\n\n## Stereochemistry creates a fourfold selectivity challenge\n\nThreonine's two chiral centers (C2 and C3) generate four stereoisomers \u2014 L-threonine (2S,3R), D-threonine (2R,3S), L-allothreonine (2S,3S), and D-allothreonine (2R,3R) \u2014 creating challenges beyond those faced by amino acids with a single stereocenter. Abiotic Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde produces roughly equal amounts of threonine and allothreonine diastereomers, each as a racemic D/L mixture, yielding approximately 25% of the biologically relevant L-threonine. Schroeder and Bada (*Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 1977) studied threonine epimerization kinetics in fossil foraminifera and showed that L-threonine epimerizes to D-allothreonine at the \u03b1-carbon faster than \u03b2-carbon racemization, meaning the diastereomer ratio shifts more rapidly than the enantiomeric ratio.\n\nPotential mechanisms for generating enantiomeric excess include **circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions, which can induce 1\u20132% ee in amino acids through preferential photodestruction (Modica et al., *Astrophysical Journal*, 2014). This small seed can be amplified: Breslow demonstrated that as little as **1% Lee can reach 95:5 L:D ratio** through simple evaporation, exploiting differential solubility of racemic versus enantiopure crystals. Pyrite's asymmetric photocatalysis (14.5\u201342.4% ee for D-amino acids) represents a mineral-based alternative. However, for threonine specifically, aqueous alteration on meteorite parent bodies promotes racemization of amino acids with \u03b1-hydrogen atoms, meaning any original ee would erode over geological timescales.\n\n---\n\n## Stability, concentration, and the fundamental bottlenecks\n\nThreonine faces several interrelated challenges that constrain its prebiotic accumulation and utilization.\n\n**Thermal instability** is the most severe constraint. Threonine's \u03b2-hydroxyl group enables rapid \u03b2-elimination yielding dehydroaminobutyric acid, analogous to serine's well-characterized decomposition. K\u00f6rner (*ChemSusChem*, 2021) noted that **no systematic investigation of threonine decomposition products under hydrothermal conditions had been performed** as of that date \u2014 a remarkable gap. What is known places threonine among the most labile proteinogenic amino acids: in dry heating studies (80\u2013180\u00b0C), it ranks below most nonpolar and acidic amino acids in stability. Truong et al. (*Icarus*, 2019) established that threonine and aspartic acid cannot persist beyond 1 billion years at 273 K, making them the least durable proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 critical for both origin-of-life scenarios and biosignature detection on icy ocean worlds like Europa and Enceladus.\n\nThe **concentration problem** applies broadly to prebiotic amino acids but affects threonine acutely given its instability. At estimated prebiotic ocean concentrations of ~10\u207b\u2074 M glycine, Ba\u00fa et al. calculated that \"tens of thousands of terrestrial prebiotic oceans would not have sufficed to obtain a single Gly\u2089 molecule at equilibrium.\" Solutions include mineral surface adsorption (layered double hydroxides can concentrate, align, and template amino acids per Erastova et al., *Nature Communications*, 2017), eutectic freezing in ice channels, evaporitic pool concentration via wet-dry cycling, thermophoretic concentration in hydrothermal micropores (~5,000-fold per Lane and Martin), and aerosol chemistry at air-water interfaces.\n\nThe **selectivity problem** \u2014 producing threonine specifically rather than complex mixtures \u2014 remains largely unsolved. The cyanosulfidic pathway offers the most promising selectivity through its constrained reaction network, but still produces mixtures. Islam, Bu\u010dar, and Powner (*Nature Chemistry*, 2017) demonstrated that 2-aminothiazole selectively sequesters glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures, potentially providing a physicochemical selection mechanism. The **water problem** (condensation reactions disfavored in aqueous solution, with \u0394G \u2248 +3.5 kcal/mol for glycine dimerization) applies to subsequent peptide incorporation. Proposed solutions include wet-dry cycling, depsipeptide intermediates (ester bonds formed first, then converted to amides), thioester chemistry, and aminonitrile coupling in water (Canavelli, Islam, and Powner, *Nature*, 2019).\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThreonine's prebiotic synthesis is better understood than for most proteinogenic amino acids, primarily thanks to the cyanosulfidic framework that connects its formation to the same chemistry producing RNA precursors. The Ritson-Sutherland pathway through lactaldehyde provides a complete, experimentally validated route from HCN to the threonine aminonitrile using only prebiotically available materials. Spark discharge experiments confirm that electrical energy acting on simple gas mixtures \u2014 particularly those containing H\u2082S \u2014 produces threonine alongside dozens of other amino acids. Racemic threonine in the pristine CR2 meteorite GRA 95229 demonstrates that abiotic synthesis occurs naturally in asteroid parent bodies.\n\nThree critical gaps remain. First, threonine's thermal and hydrolytic instability means it must be synthesized and utilized on timescales shorter than its decomposition half-life \u2014 a constraint that strongly favors lower-temperature environments (alkaline vents, surface pools, ice) over high-temperature hydrothermal settings. Second, the systematic study of threonine decomposition products under prebiotic conditions has never been performed, leaving the kinetics and products of its degradation poorly constrained. Third, achieving the stereochemical selectivity needed to produce predominantly L-threonine (one of four stereoisomers) from racemic abiotic synthesis remains an open problem, though pyrite's asymmetric photocatalysis and CPL-seeded amplification mechanisms offer partial solutions. The convergence of cyanosulfidic chemistry, meteorite analysis, and mineral catalysis research is steadily narrowing these gaps, positioning threonine as a tractable case study for understanding how biological amino acids emerged from prebiotic chemistry.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and chemically mixed. Positives: it is connected, has sufficient node count, contains multiple true hubs around HCN, acetaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, aminonitrile, and pyruvate, and includes several convergent routes that match the literature theme of threonine emerging from a shared prebiotic network rather than a single linear path. Environmental interconnection is also a major strength: hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced feedstocks, surface chemistry performs UV/cyanosulfidic transformations, and biochemical/prebiotic stages complete lower-temperature conversion to the target. The inclusion of the lactaldehyde Strecker route, glyceraldehyde route, Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route, and a Miller-type route aligns well with the deep research findings. However, the network falls short of full approval because several key reactions are overcompressed or insufficiently supported. In particular, rxn_002 and rxn_003 assign broad hydrothermal formation of acetate, pyruvate, acetaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde with limited specificity; rxn_008 is mechanistically unclear for glycine formation; rxn_011 is the weakest step, as direct prebiotic synthesis of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate from pyruvate/acetaldehyde/glycolaldehyde is not convincingly established; and rxn_012 inappropriately merges three distinct final routes into one reaction node. Literature alignment is moderate to good overall, especially for cyanosulfidic and hydantoin logic, but the network underrepresents key details emphasized in the research such as Cu(I)-cyanide/H2S photoredox conditions, methane-rich spark discharge conditions, and threonine instability at elevated temperature. The network would become clearly approvable if the terminal chemistry were disentangled and speculative hydrothermal or keto-acid steps were either better justified or separated from the strongest literature-backed routes.\n- Issues: ['This pathway captures the desired hydrothermal-to-surface relay very well, but its chemistry is weakened by speculative hydrothermal production of acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde from acetate/CO2/H2 and especially by the bundled formation of pyruvate in rxn_002. Hydrothermal delivery of reduced carbon feedstocks is plausible, but the specific carbon-flow assignments here are looser than the literature. Downstream surface conversion to lactaldehyde and threonine aminonitrile is stronger.', 'The pathway is conceptually coherent because hydrothermal chemistry seeds reduced feedstocks and surface photochemistry converts them into sugar/aminonitrile intermediates. However, the hydrothermal route to glycolaldehyde is underjustified and the network blurs whether glycolaldehyde arises hydrothermally or by canonical HCN photohomologation. The route remains plausible as a network path, but not all steps are equally supported.', 'This hydrothermal-to-hydantoin route benefits from good environmental connectivity but inherits the speculative hydrothermal aldehyde formation problem. The Bucherer-Bergs section is reasonable; the upstream hydrothermal sourcing of the specific aldehyde pool is less secure. It is a valid network route but not one of the better-supported ones.', \"This is the weakest major route. The literature supports reductive amination of alpha-keto acids in principle, but the network's specific formation of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate from pyruvate, acetaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde in rxn_011 is not convincingly established. The final lumped step to threonine also obscures whether reductive amination of the keto acid is truly operating. This pathway is better treated as speculative support rather than a main route.\", 'This route is poorly specified. The named pathway suggests glycine-acetaldehyde aldol chemistry, but the actual network lacks a clear glycine + acetaldehyde -> threonine step and instead diverts through formamide, a compressed glycine synthesis, and a weakly supported keto-acid assembly. The literature itself notes that the reverse aldol route is conceptually possible but not prebiotically demonstrated. As encoded, this pathway is not convincing.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network centers on literature-supported prebiotic routes in which hydrothermal environments generate and concentrate reduced C1/C2 feedstocks and keto acids, surface cyanosulfidic and discharge-driven chemistry converts these into aldehydes and aminonitriles, and lower-temperature biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, reductive amination, and incorporation before threonine decomposes. The densest convergence occurs at HCN, acetaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile. Ten distinct pathways are encoded by combining experimentally demonstrated routes: (i) lactaldehyde Strecker via cyanosulfidic photoreduction, (ii) glyceraldehyde Strecker, (iii) spark-discharge generation of the same precursor pool, (iv) Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin chemistry from lactaldehyde, (v) HCN-polymer hydrolysate entry into the aminonitrile pool, (vi) speculative but literature-grounded \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate reductive amination, and (vii-x) additional distinct route variants differing by environmental sourcing of shared hubs and downstream conversion sequence. High-temperature vent chemistry is restricted to feedstock generation/concentration because the literature emphasizes threonine instability above moderate temperatures.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate/formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S phases yields reduced C1 species including formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite and mackinawite are documented Hadean vent minerals and analogs of Fe-S enzyme clusters; alkaline vent settings favor exergonic amino-acid precursor synthesis and reduced carbon generation (White et al., 2015; Shock and Canovas, 1998; Lane and Martin, 2012). This reaction is used only as feedstock generation, consistent with the literature caution that high-temperature settings are better for precursor supply than final threonine accumulation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of HCN-derived aldehyde pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu(I)-cyanide / cyanosulfidic mineral context)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system under UV; TiO2 as UV-active surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, H2S as reductant, phosphate-buffered shallow pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iterative photoredox homologation of HCN generates formaldehyde-equivalent chemistry and then glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and acetaldehyde in the cyanosulfidic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland showed UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide with H2S converts HCN into aldehydes including glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde; Patel et al. integrated this chemistry into a broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism that also gives glyceraldehyde-class carbohydrate precursors. TiO2 is included as a plausible UV-active mineral surface in surface settings without changing the literature-grounded Cu(I)-cyanide photoredox core (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Dunn et al., 1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu(I)-cyanide / cyanosulfidic mineral context)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox milieu\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed cyanosulfidic pool with H2S present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to acetaldehyde forms acetaldehyde cyanohydrin.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the specific precursor step used in the Ritson-Sutherland route to lactaldehyde. It is part of the experimentally characterized cyanosulfidic sequence linking acetaldehyde to threonine precursors (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013). Montmorillonite is included as a concentrating mineral surface for shallow-pool chemistry, but the key support is the cyanohydrin chemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu(I)-cyanide / cyanosulfidic mineral context)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with H2S reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"2 h irradiation; reported lactaldehyde yield 19%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox reduction of the cyanohydrin intermediate gives 2-hydroxypropanal.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland experimentally demonstrated conversion of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde at 19% yield after 2 h UV irradiation in H2S/Cu(I)-cyanide photoredox chemistry. This is the strongest literature-supported threonine-specific precursor step (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"classic Strecker sequence via imine formation followed by cyanide addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium, followed by cyanide addition to give 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research identifies lactaldehyde as the direct aldehyde precursor for classic Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile, which then hydrolyzes to threonine and allothreonine as racemic diastereomeric mixtures (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015). Montmorillonite is used here as a concentrating surface consistent with surface pool chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate stabilization of sugar aldehyde\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow UV-exposed pool; glyceraldehyde stabilized against side reactions by borate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde enters Strecker chemistry directly to the same threonine aminonitrile pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. explicitly noted a parallel route in which glyceraldehyde, rather than lactaldehyde, yields the threonine aminonitrile. Borate inclusion follows the literature emphasis on borate stabilization of sugar aldehydes in surface environments and helps preserve glyceraldehyde as a branch point connecting RNA and amino-acid precursor chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Islam et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated pool or interface; low-to-moderate temperature to limit threonine decomposition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile into the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine/allothreonine is the terminal step of the Strecker route. Mild post-synthetic conditions are chosen because the literature stresses threonine fragility and poor persistence at elevated temperatures (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Truong et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ammonium carbonate/CO2-rich aqueous evaporitic setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-type trapping of amino acid precursor as hydantoin thermodynamic sink\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide and ammonium/carbonate equivalents to form a cyclic hydantoin intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research identifies the Bucherer-Bergs route as a plausible threonine pathway in which lactaldehyde yields 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin prior to hydrolysis. The hydantoin acts as a thermodynamic sink and mirrors the demonstrated \u03b1-keto-acid-to-amino-acid chemistry reported by Pulletikurti et al. for related systems (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; Lerner and Cooper, 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild hydrolysis after concentration in pools or interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ring opening and hydrolytic conversion of the hydantoin yields the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows the Bucherer-Bergs logic emphasized in the research report. While direct threonine-specific hydrolysis data are inferred by analogy, the hydantoin route is specifically proposed for threonine from lactaldehyde and is supported by hydantoin occurrence in carbonaceous chondrites (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; Lerner and Cooper, 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark discharge generation of HCN and acetaldehyde precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable discharge plasma with aqueous condensation\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge in CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3 or CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S mixtures\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"post-discharge aqueous collection; H2S-containing experiments especially favorable for hydroxylated amino-acid formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge in reduced gas mixtures generates HCN, NH3, aldehydes, and related Strecker precursors that condense in aqueous phase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ring et al. confirmed threonine/allothreonine formation in spark-discharge experiments from CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3, and Parker et al. detected threonine in Stanley Miller's H2S-containing archived samples. This node supplies an alternative surface source of the same hubs used in Strecker chemistry without inventing unsupported intermediates (Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymerization and hydrolytic release of glycine-rich amino acid mixture\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"polymerization/hydrolysis in aqueous or frozen-concentrated settings\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis; compatible with eutectic concentration or surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomers form heterogeneous nitrile polymers that upon hydrolysis release amino acids, especially glycine and other proteinogenic members.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ruiz-Bermejo et al. reviewed HCN polymer hydrolysates and found 12 proteinogenic amino acids including threonine under multiple conditions, with glycine consistently abundant. This reaction is used conservatively as a literature-supported entry into the amino-acid pool, not as a selective threonine route (Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013; Miyakawa et al., 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires high glycine concentration or catalytic assistance; thermodynamically unfavorable; likely gives threonine/allothreonine mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reverse of threonine aldol cleavage: carbon-carbon bond formation between glycine-derived enamine/enol equivalent and acetaldehyde gives \u03b2-hydroxy-\u03b1-amino acid skeleton.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research explicitly identifies glycine + acetaldehyde aldol condensation as a conceptually simple route but notes that no purely prebiotic demonstration has been reported and the reaction is thermodynamically unfavorable. It is therefore retained as a speculative but literature-grounded branch rather than a primary route (Fesko, 2016; Koga and Naraoka, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of \u03b1-keto acid precursor and reductive amination to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K for reductive amination component; moderate hydrothermal interface\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/Fe0/Ni-like reductive amination logic in anoxic water\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"network-completion step; low-temperature interface preferred because threonine is unstable at higher temperatures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced-carbon feedstocks are assembled to the \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate level and then aminated under Fe2+/H2-driven conditions to threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included only as a cautious, partly speculative connector because the literature establishes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids generally, but not specifically for 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate. Muchowska et al. demonstrated Fe2+-promoted reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70\u00b0C, Kaur et al. extended H2-driven reductive amination over nickel at 22\u00b0C pH 8, and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user showed CO-dependent \u03b1-amino acid formation on Ni-Fe precipitates. The threonine-specific precursor is therefore plausible but not directly demonstrated; this pathway is intentionally flagged as weaker than the Strecker and hydantoin routes (Muchowska et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024; Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2006).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN photoredox chemistry generates acetaldehyde, which forms a cyanohydrin, is photoreduced to lactaldehyde, then enters Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"The cyanosulfidic network also furnishes glyceraldehyde, which directly gives threonine aminonitrile under Strecker conditions followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde from cyanosulfidic photochemistry is trapped as a hydantoin and then hydrolyzed to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge to lactaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Electrical discharge supplies HCN and acetaldehyde, which feed the lactaldehyde Strecker sequence to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge to Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark-generated HCN and acetaldehyde are routed through lactaldehyde and hydantoin intermediates to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal feedstock relay into cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies reduced carbon to surface cyanosulfidic chemistry, which then proceeds through the lactaldehyde Strecker route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal feedstock relay into glyceraldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon contributes to the surface HCN homologation network, converging on glyceraldehyde and then threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymer hydrolysate plus acetaldehyde aldol route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN polymerization/hydrolysis supplies glycine, which combines with acetaldehyde from the cyanosulfidic aldehyde pool in a speculative reverse threonine-aldol path.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge glycine-acetaldehyde aldol route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark discharge provides acetaldehyde while HCN oligomer hydrolysis provides glycine, enabling the same speculative aldol access to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"\u03b1-Keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"A weaker but literature-grounded metabolic analog route in which \u03b1-keto acid chemistry under Fe2+/H2-reducing conditions yields threonine from its keto precursor.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network centers on literature-supported prebiotic routes in which hydrothermal environments generate and concentrate reduced C1/C2 feedstocks and keto acids, surface cyanosulfidic and discharge-driven chemistry converts these into aldehydes and aminonitriles, and lower-temperature biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, reductive amination, and incorporation before threonine decomposes. The densest convergence occurs at HCN, acetaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile. Ten distinct pathways are encoded by combining experimentally demonstrated routes: (i) lactaldehyde Strecker via cyanosulfidic photoreduction, (ii) glyceraldehyde Strecker, (iii) spark-discharge generation of the same precursor pool, (iv) Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin chemistry from lactaldehyde, (v) HCN-polymer hydrolysate entry into the aminonitrile pool, (vi) speculative but literature-grounded \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate reductive amination, and (vii-x) additional distinct route variants differing by environmental sourcing of shared hubs and downstream conversion sequence. High-temperature vent chemistry is restricted to feedstock generation/concentration because the literature emphasizes threonine instability above moderate temperatures.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H6N2O3", "iupac_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S phases yields reduced C1 species including formate.", "reasoning": "Greigite and mackinawite are documented Hadean vent minerals and analogs of Fe-S enzyme clusters; alkaline vent settings favor exergonic amino-acid precursor synthesis and reduced carbon generation (White et al., 2015; Shock and Canovas, 1998; Lane and Martin, 2012). This reaction is used only as feedstock generation, consistent with the literature caution that high-temperature settings are better for precursor supply than final threonine accumulation."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of HCN-derived aldehyde pool", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu(I)-cyanide / cyanosulfidic mineral context)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system under UV; TiO2 as UV-active surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, H2S as reductant, phosphate-buffered shallow pool"}, "mechanism": "Iterative photoredox homologation of HCN generates formaldehyde-equivalent chemistry and then glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and acetaldehyde in the cyanosulfidic network.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland showed UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide with H2S converts HCN into aldehydes including glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde; Patel et al. integrated this chemistry into a broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism that also gives glyceraldehyde-class carbohydrate precursors. TiO2 is included as a plausible UV-active mineral surface in surface settings without changing the literature-grounded Cu(I)-cyanide photoredox core (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Dunn et al., 1981)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu(I)-cyanide / cyanosulfidic mineral context)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox milieu", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed cyanosulfidic pool with H2S present"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to acetaldehyde forms acetaldehyde cyanohydrin.", "reasoning": "This is the specific precursor step used in the Ritson-Sutherland route to lactaldehyde. It is part of the experimentally characterized cyanosulfidic sequence linking acetaldehyde to threonine precursors (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013). Montmorillonite is included as a concentrating mineral surface for shallow-pool chemistry, but the key support is the cyanohydrin chemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu(I)-cyanide / cyanosulfidic mineral context)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with H2S reductant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "2 h irradiation; reported lactaldehyde yield 19%"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox reduction of the cyanohydrin intermediate gives 2-hydroxypropanal.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland experimentally demonstrated conversion of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde at 19% yield after 2 h UV irradiation in H2S/Cu(I)-cyanide photoredox chemistry. This is the strongest literature-supported threonine-specific precursor step (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "classic Strecker sequence via imine formation followed by cyanide addition"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium, followed by cyanide addition to give 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "The deep research identifies lactaldehyde as the direct aldehyde precursor for classic Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile, which then hydrolyzes to threonine and allothreonine as racemic diastereomeric mixtures (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015). Montmorillonite is used here as a concentrating surface consistent with surface pool chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate stabilization of sugar aldehyde", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow UV-exposed pool; glyceraldehyde stabilized against side reactions by borate"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde enters Strecker chemistry directly to the same threonine aminonitrile pool.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. explicitly noted a parallel route in which glyceraldehyde, rather than lactaldehyde, yields the threonine aminonitrile. Borate inclusion follows the literature emphasis on borate stabilization of sugar aldehydes in surface environments and helps preserve glyceraldehyde as a branch point connecting RNA and amino-acid precursor chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Islam et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated pool or interface; low-to-moderate temperature to limit threonine decomposition"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile into the amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine/allothreonine is the terminal step of the Strecker route. Mild post-synthetic conditions are chosen because the literature stresses threonine fragility and poor persistence at elevated temperatures (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Truong et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ammonium carbonate/CO2-rich aqueous evaporitic setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Bucherer-Bergs-type trapping of amino acid precursor as hydantoin thermodynamic sink"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide and ammonium/carbonate equivalents to form a cyclic hydantoin intermediate.", "reasoning": "The deep research identifies the Bucherer-Bergs route as a plausible threonine pathway in which lactaldehyde yields 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin prior to hydrolysis. The hydantoin acts as a thermodynamic sink and mirrors the demonstrated \u03b1-keto-acid-to-amino-acid chemistry reported by Pulletikurti et al. for related systems (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; Lerner and Cooper, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild hydrolysis after concentration in pools or interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Ring opening and hydrolytic conversion of the hydantoin yields the amino acid.", "reasoning": "This step follows the Bucherer-Bergs logic emphasized in the research report. While direct threonine-specific hydrolysis data are inferred by analogy, the hydantoin route is specifically proposed for threonine from lactaldehyde and is supported by hydantoin occurrence in carbonaceous chondrites (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; Lerner and Cooper, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Spark discharge generation of HCN and acetaldehyde precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable discharge plasma with aqueous condensation", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge in CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3 or CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S mixtures", "aqueous": "true", "other": "post-discharge aqueous collection; H2S-containing experiments especially favorable for hydroxylated amino-acid formation"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge in reduced gas mixtures generates HCN, NH3, aldehydes, and related Strecker precursors that condense in aqueous phase.", "reasoning": "Ring et al. confirmed threonine/allothreonine formation in spark-discharge experiments from CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3, and Parker et al. detected threonine in Stanley Miller's H2S-containing archived samples. This node supplies an alternative surface source of the same hubs used in Strecker chemistry without inventing unsupported intermediates (Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "HCN polymerization and hydrolytic release of glycine-rich amino acid mixture", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "polymerization/hydrolysis in aqueous or frozen-concentrated settings", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis; compatible with eutectic concentration or surface pools"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomers form heterogeneous nitrile polymers that upon hydrolysis release amino acids, especially glycine and other proteinogenic members.", "reasoning": "Ruiz-Bermejo et al. reviewed HCN polymer hydrolysates and found 12 proteinogenic amino acids including threonine under multiple conditions, with glycine consistently abundant. This reaction is used conservatively as a literature-supported entry into the amino-acid pool, not as a selective threonine route (Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013; Miyakawa et al., 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "requires high glycine concentration or catalytic assistance; thermodynamically unfavorable; likely gives threonine/allothreonine mixture"}, "mechanism": "Reverse of threonine aldol cleavage: carbon-carbon bond formation between glycine-derived enamine/enol equivalent and acetaldehyde gives \u03b2-hydroxy-\u03b1-amino acid skeleton.", "reasoning": "The deep research explicitly identifies glycine + acetaldehyde aldol condensation as a conceptually simple route but notes that no purely prebiotic demonstration has been reported and the reaction is thermodynamically unfavorable. It is therefore retained as a speculative but literature-grounded branch rather than a primary route (Fesko, 2016; Koga and Naraoka, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of \u03b1-keto acid precursor and reductive amination to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K for reductive amination component; moderate hydrothermal interface", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe2+/Fe0/Ni-like reductive amination logic in anoxic water", "aqueous": "true", "other": "network-completion step; low-temperature interface preferred because threonine is unstable at higher temperatures"}, "mechanism": "Reduced-carbon feedstocks are assembled to the \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate level and then aminated under Fe2+/H2-driven conditions to threonine.", "reasoning": "This step is included only as a cautious, partly speculative connector because the literature establishes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids generally, but not specifically for 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate. Muchowska et al. demonstrated Fe2+-promoted reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70\u00b0C, Kaur et al. extended H2-driven reductive amination over nickel at 22\u00b0C pH 8, and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user showed CO-dependent \u03b1-amino acid formation on Ni-Fe precipitates. The threonine-specific precursor is therefore plausible but not directly demonstrated; this pathway is intentionally flagged as weaker than the Strecker and hydantoin routes (Muchowska et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024; Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2006)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "HCN photoredox chemistry generates acetaldehyde, which forms a cyanohydrin, is photoreduced to lactaldehyde, then enters Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Glyceraldehyde Strecker route", "description": "The cyanosulfidic network also furnishes glyceraldehyde, which directly gives threonine aminonitrile under Strecker conditions followed by hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Lactaldehyde Bucherer-Bergs route", "description": "Lactaldehyde from cyanosulfidic photochemistry is trapped as a hydantoin and then hydrolyzed to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Spark-discharge to lactaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Electrical discharge supplies HCN and acetaldehyde, which feed the lactaldehyde Strecker sequence to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Spark-discharge to Bucherer-Bergs route", "description": "Spark-generated HCN and acetaldehyde are routed through lactaldehyde and hydantoin intermediates to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal feedstock relay into cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies reduced carbon to surface cyanosulfidic chemistry, which then proceeds through the lactaldehyde Strecker route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal feedstock relay into glyceraldehyde route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon contributes to the surface HCN homologation network, converging on glyceraldehyde and then threonine aminonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "HCN polymer hydrolysate plus acetaldehyde aldol route", "description": "HCN polymerization/hydrolysis supplies glycine, which combines with acetaldehyde from the cyanosulfidic aldehyde pool in a speculative reverse threonine-aldol path.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_005"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Spark-discharge glycine-acetaldehyde aldol route", "description": "Spark discharge provides acetaldehyde while HCN oligomer hydrolysis provides glycine, enabling the same speculative aldol access to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "\u03b1-Keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate reductive amination route", "description": "A weaker but literature-grounded metabolic analog route in which \u03b1-keto acid chemistry under Fe2+/H2-reducing conditions yields threonine from its keto precursor.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_015"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_003", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol