{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T02:55:36.929608", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network centers on literature-supported prebiotic routes in which hydrothermal environments generate and concentrate reduced C1/C2 feedstocks and keto acids, surface cyanosulfidic and discharge-driven chemistry converts these into aldehydes and aminonitriles, and lower-temperature biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, reductive amination, and incorporation before threonine decomposes. The densest convergence occurs at HCN, acetaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile. Ten distinct pathways are encoded by combining experimentally demonstrated routes: (i) lactaldehyde Strecker via cyanosulfidic photoreduction, (ii) glyceraldehyde Strecker, (iii) spark-discharge generation of the same precursor pool, (iv) Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin chemistry from lactaldehyde, (v) HCN-polymer hydrolysate entry into the aminonitrile pool, (vi) speculative but literature-grounded \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate reductive amination, and (vii-x) additional distinct route variants differing by environmental sourcing of shared hubs and downstream conversion sequence. High-temperature vent chemistry is restricted to feedstock generation/concentration because the literature emphasizes threonine instability above moderate temperatures.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: CH2O2 (formate/formic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C3H5NO (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: NH3 (ammonia) [st